{"title_page": "Certaldo", "text_new": "{{Infobox Italian comune\n| name                = Certaldo\n| official_name       = Comune di Certaldo\n| native_name         = \n| image_skyline       = Certaldo alta panorama2008.jpg\n| imagesize           = \n| image_alt           = \n| image_caption       = \n| image_shield        = Certaldo-Stemma.svg\n| shield_alt          = \n| image_map           = \n| map_alt             = \n| map_caption         = \n| pushpin_label_position = \n| pushpin_map_alt     = \n| coordinates         = {{coord|43|32|52|N|11|2|28|E|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_footnotes = \n| region              = [[Tuscany]]\n| metropolitan_city   = [[Metropolitan City of Florence|Florence]] (FI)\n| frazioni            = Bagnano, Fiano, Marcialla (part), Sciano\n| mayor_party         = [[Democratic Party (Italy)|PD]]\n| mayor               = Giacomo Cucini\n| area_footnotes      = \n| area_total_km2      = 75.28\n| population_footnotes = <ref name=\"istat\">All demographics and other statistics: Italian statistical institute [[National Institute of Statistics (Italy)|Istat]].</ref>\n| population_total    = 16004\n| population_as_of    = 30 June 2017\n| pop_density_footnotes = \n| population_demonym  = Certaldesi\n| elevation_footnotes = \n| elevation_m         = 67\n| twin1               = \n| twin1_country       = \n| saint               = St. Thomas the Apostle\n| day                 = July 3\n| postal_code         = 50052\n| area_code           = 0571\n| website             = {{official website|http://certaldo.empolese-valdelsa.it/}}{{dead link|date=October 2016}}\n| footnotes           = \n}}'''Certaldo''' is a town and ''[[comune]]'' of [[Tuscany]], [[Italy]], in the [[Metropolitan City of Florence]], in the middle of [[Valdelsa]]. It is about {{convert|35|km|mi}} southwest of the Florence Duomo.<ref>{{cite EB1911 |wstitle=Certaldo |volume=5 |page=762}}</ref>\n\nIt is 50 minutes by rail and 35 minutes by car southwest of [[Florence]], and it is 40 minutes by rail north of [[Siena]].\n\nIt was home to the family of [[Giovanni Boccaccio]], author of the ''[[Decameron]]''. He died at his home inside the town and was buried here in 1375. The actor [[Ernesto Calindri]] was also born in Certaldo.\n\n== Geography ==\nThe town of Certaldo is divided into upper and lower parts. The lower part is called Certaldo Basso, whilst the medieval upper part is called Certaldo Alto. Certaldo Alto has limited vehicular access, for use by residents only. Visitors can park outside the walls or in the lower part and go to Certaldo Alto by the [[Certaldo funicular]].\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Etruscan-Roman period ===\nCertaldo had [[Etruscan civilization|Etruscan]]-[[Roman civilisation|Roman]] origins, as shown by the numerous archaeological finds that are scattered around the city's territory, including ceramics, utensils and Etruscan tombs, some of which were found just recently.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Topografia Storica della Val d'Elsa in periodo etrusco|last=De Marinis|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> The Etruscan origins were discovered mostly thanks to the [[Toponymy]] of some localities and streams, for example the Agliena and the Elsa river (which flow near Certaldo), and the foodstuffs deposits in the hills. There are two hills in Certaldo where Etruscan tombs have been found, Poggio del Boccaccio and Poggio alle Fate. There was also a necropolis. All of the finds of Etruscan-Roman origin are today kept in the ground floor of the Palazzo Pretorio, in the medieval part of the town.\n\n*Boccaccio's house, of red brick, like the other old houses here, was restored in 1823 and furnished with old furniture. A statue of him was erected in the main square in 1875.\n*The Palazzo Pretorio, or Vicariale, the residence of the Florentine governors, recently restored to its original condition, has a picturesque facade adorned with ceramic coats of arms, and in the interior are various frescoes dating from the 13th to the 16th century.\n\n== Culture ==\nThe town hosts several festivals a year. The largest and most famous is [[Mercantia]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.turismo.intoscana.it/allthingstuscany/aroundtuscany/mercantia-is-back-in-certaldo/# |title=Mercantia |access-date=2013-09-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130726092800/http://www.turismo.intoscana.it/allthingstuscany/aroundtuscany/mercantia-is-back-in-certaldo/# |archive-date=2013-07-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref> a week-long party in Certaldo Alto. It involves numerous street performers from across Italy, Europe and even the Americas.\n\n== Twin towns ==\n*{{flagicon|GER}} [[Neuruppin]], Germany\n*{{flagicon|Japan}} [[Kanra, Gunma|Kanramachi]], Japan\n*{{flagicon|UK}} [[Canterbury]], United Kingdom\n\n== References ==\n{{commons category|Certaldo}}\n<references/>\n\n{{Province of Florence}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Tuscany]]\n\n\n{{Tuscany-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Italian comune\n| name                = Certaldo\n| official_name       = Comune di Certaldo\n| native_name         = \n| image_skyline       = Certaldo alta panorama2008.jpg\n| imagesize           = \n| image_alt           = \n| image_caption       = \n| image_shield        = Certaldo-Stemma.svg\n| shield_alt          = \n| image_map           = \n| map_alt             = \n| map_caption         = \n| pushpin_label_position = \n| pushpin_map_alt     = \n| coordinates         = {{coord|43|32|52|N|11|2|28|E|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_footnotes = \n| region              = [[Tuscany]]\n| metropolitan_city   = [[Metropolitan City of Florence|Florence]] (FI)\n| frazioni            = Bagnano, Fiano, Marcialla (part), Sciano\n| mayor_party         = [[Democratic Party (Italy)|PD]]\n| mayor               = Giacomo Cucini\n| area_footnotes      = \n| area_total_km2      = 75.28\n| population_footnotes = <ref name=\"istat\">All demographics and other statistics: Italian statistical institute [[National Institute of Statistics (Italy)|Istat]].</ref>\n| population_total    = 16004\n| population_as_of    = 30 June 2017\n| pop_density_footnotes = \n| population_demonym  = Certaldesi\n| elevation_footnotes = \n| elevation_m         = 67\n| twin1               = \n| twin1_country       = \n| saint               = St. Thomas the Apostle\n| day                 = July 3\n| postal_code         = 50052\n| area_code           = 0571\n| website             = {{official website|http://certaldo.empolese-valdelsa.it/}}{{dead link|date=October 2016}}\n| footnotes           = \n}}'''Certaldo''' is a town and ''[[comune]]'' of [[Tuscany]], [[Italy]], in the [[Metropolitan City of Florence]], in the middle of [[Valdelsa]]. It is about {{convert|35|km|mi}} southwest of the Florence Duomo.<ref>{{cite EB1911 |wstitle=Certaldo |volume=5 |page=762}}</ref>\n\nIt is 50 minutes by rail and 35 minutes by car southwest of [[Florence]], and it is 40 minutes by rail north of [[Siena]].\n\nIt was home to the family of [[Giovanni Boccaccio]], author of the ''[[Decameron]]''. He died at his home inside the town and was buried here in 1375. The actor [[Ernesto Calindri]] was also born in Certaldo.\n\n== Geography ==\nThe town of Certaldo is divided into upper and lower parts. The lower part is called Certaldo Basso, whilst the medieval upper part is called Certaldo Alto. Certaldo Alto has limited vehicular access, for use by residents only. Visitors can park outside the walls or in the lower part and go to Certaldo Alto by the [[Certaldo funicular]].\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Etruscan-Roman period ===\nCertaldo had [[Etruscan civilization|Etruscan]]-[[Roman civilisation|Roman]] origins, as shown by the numerous archaeological finds that are scattered around the city's territory, including ceramics, utensils and Etruscan tombs, some of which were found just recently.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Topografia Storica della Val d'Elsa in periodo etrusco|last=De Marinis|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> The Etruscan origins were discovered mostly thanks to the [[Toponymy]] of some localities and streams, for example the Agliena and the Elsa river (which flow near Certaldo), and the foodstuffs deposits in the hills. There was also a necropolis. All of the finds of Etruscan-Roman origin are today kept in the ground floor of the Palazzo Pretorio, in the medieval part of the town.\n\n*Boccaccio's house, of red brick, like the other old houses here, was restored in 1823 and furnished with old furniture. A statue of him was erected in the main square in 1875.\n*The Palazzo Pretorio, or Vicariale, the residence of the Florentine governors, recently restored to its original condition, has a picturesque facade adorned with ceramic coats of arms, and in the interior are various frescoes dating from the 13th to the 16th century.\n\n== Culture ==\nThe town hosts several festivals a year. The largest and most famous is [[Mercantia]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.turismo.intoscana.it/allthingstuscany/aroundtuscany/mercantia-is-back-in-certaldo/# |title=Mercantia |access-date=2013-09-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130726092800/http://www.turismo.intoscana.it/allthingstuscany/aroundtuscany/mercantia-is-back-in-certaldo/# |archive-date=2013-07-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref> a week-long party in Certaldo Alto. It involves numerous street performers from across Italy, Europe and even the Americas.\n\n== Twin towns ==\n*{{flagicon|GER}} [[Neuruppin]], Germany\n*{{flagicon|Japan}} [[Kanra, Gunma|Kanramachi]], Japan\n*{{flagicon|UK}} [[Canterbury]], United Kingdom\n\n== References ==\n{{commons category|Certaldo}}\n<references/>\n\n{{Province of Florence}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Tuscany]]\n\n\n{{Tuscany-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Fizzdom", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEtruscan-Roman period", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Certaldo"}
